<P>THE MS. found by Adeline, the preceding night, h<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">d <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">veral times occurred to her recollection in the cour&s;e of the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ay, but &s;he had then been either too much intere&s;ted by the events of the moment, of too apprehen&s;ive of interruption, to attempt a peru&s;al of it. She now took it from the drawer in which it had been depo&s;ited, and intending only to look cur|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ily over the few fir&s;t pages &s;at down with it by her bed &s;ide.</P>
<P>She opened it with an eagerne&s;s of inquiry, which the di&s;col|oured and almo&s;t obliterated ink but &s;lowly gratified. The fir&s;t words on the page were entirely lo&s;t, but tho&s;e that ap|p<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ared to commence the narrative were as follows:</P>
