<P>The &s;pot he now inhabited, the &s;urrounding &s;cenery, the ro|mantic beauties of the neighbouring walks, were dear to La Luc, for they had once been loved by Clara; they had been the &s;cenes of her tenderne&s;s, and of his happine&s;s.</P>
<P>His chateau &s;tood on the borders of a &s;mall lake that was al|mo&s;t environed by mountains of &s;tupendous height, which, &s;hoot|ing
